00:01:29.850 --> 00:01:31.530
by Dario Alfe and Mike Gillan.

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:36.240
So this is actually a cut
out of the Earth interior,

00:01:36.240 --> 00:01:38.910
and in case you're not familiar
with this, the way it works

00:01:38.910 --> 00:01:43.200
is that we are actually sitting
on a large liquid region.

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:47.160
So you see, on top here, we
have sort of the Earth crust.

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:51.210
And what is very important
for us is actually

00:01:51.210 --> 00:01:54.780
this region, dark
yellow and light yellow,

00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:58.470
in which we have the so-called
core of the planet that

00:01:58.470 --> 00:02:02.640
is mainly constituted by iron.

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:06.450
Iron actually is a
very stable nucleus.

00:02:06.450 --> 00:02:09.840
So instead of the early
formation of stars,

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:14.040
it's one of the elements
that sort of, once created,

00:02:14.040 --> 00:02:17.530
sort of was more
stable than the other.

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:19.140
And what happens
in our planet is

00:02:19.140 --> 00:02:22.830
that we have a sort of
increasing pressure going

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:26.100
inside, and the inner
core, so-called,

00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:30.180
again, sort of mostly
iron is actually solid.

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:35.220
And we know very well
what is the pressure here

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:41.190
at the boundary between the
outer core and the inner core.

00:02:41.190 --> 00:02:42.780
This part is liquid.

00:02:42.780 --> 00:02:44.450
Pressure is increasing here.

00:02:44.450 --> 00:02:45.960
So this part is liquid.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:47.400
This part is solid.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:48.810
It's mostly iron.

00:02:48.810 --> 00:02:51.090
And for this sort of
case, we'll assume

00:02:51.090 --> 00:02:53.580
that is 100% iron,
although there

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:56.940
is another problem of
really how much impurities

00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:58.050
they are diluted.

00:02:58.050 --> 00:03:02.520
And we know very well what
is the pressure there,

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:05.460
because we can sort of
look at seismic waves

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:08.880
and how seismic
waves get deflected

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:10.560
by that discontinuities.

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:14.790
And the pressure is
roughly 330 gigapascal,

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:19.500
but we actually don't know what
is the phase diagram of iron

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:20.370
at that pressure.

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:23.280
And you see, if we knew what
the phase diagram of iron

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:27.270
at that pressure was, we
could pinpoint exactly

00:03:27.270 --> 00:03:29.910
the temperature here,
because these points here

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:31.980
are sort of points
of coexistence

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:35.040
at 330 gigapascal
between the liquid

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:37.600
and the solid phase
at that boundary.

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:39.690
So if you want, by
knowing the pressure,

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:43.260
we would be able via the
phase diagram of iron

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:48.300
to actually pinpoint what is the
temperature inside the Earth.

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:51.270
And before sort of the set of
experimental and theoretical

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:54.660
work that I'll show, the
estimates, actually, for this

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:59.610
were really sort of ranging
in a very wide spectrum

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:03.900
of possibilities from 3,000
Kelvin to 8,000 Kelvin.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:06.330
And this is where sort of
our initial simulations

00:04:06.330 --> 00:04:08.940
become very useful,
because really,

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:14.070
once you believe your energy
model, there is no reason

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:16.332
to sort of think
that it would fail,

00:04:16.332 --> 00:04:17.999
either because the
pressure is too large

00:04:17.999 --> 00:04:23.040
or because the
temperature is too high.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:28.500
In all of this current
experimental capabilities

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:31.860
to study the high
pressure system,

00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:35.550
the best instrument is what is
called a diamond anvil cell.

00:04:35.550 --> 00:04:38.310
That is basically
made by 2 diamonds.

00:04:38.310 --> 00:04:42.000
So the more perfect they
are, the better that they

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.390
squeeze whatever
you're putting inside.

00:04:45.390 --> 00:04:47.370
And you know diamond
is transparent to a lot

00:04:47.370 --> 00:04:49.860
of wavelengths, so they are
very useful to probe them

00:04:49.860 --> 00:04:51.630
with spectroscopic techniques.

00:04:51.630 --> 00:04:54.940
But basically, now,
the best you can do--

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:57.300
and you still sort
of break up hundreds

00:04:57.300 --> 00:04:58.810
of diamonds in the process--

00:04:58.810 --> 00:05:02.410
is that you can get
to 300 gigapascal

00:05:02.410 --> 00:05:04.550
if you are doing this
at room temperature.

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:07.960
But as soon as you want to study
things at a higher temperature,

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:11.650
really 200 gigapascal is the
limit that you can reach.

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:15.110
Well, we want to figure
out what's happening here.

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:17.500
There are other techniques--
experimental techniques

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:23.740
to study matter under conditions
of very high pressure and very

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:28.300
high temperatures done with
what is called a gunshot

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:31.090
cannon in which you really
sort of shoot pellets

00:05:31.090 --> 00:05:33.670
and try to establish
what's going

00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:37.000
on in the instant in which
they hit their target.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.670
And so they find themselves
at very high condition

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:41.170
of pressure, but
it's very difficult

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:44.540
to get accurate
data out of this.

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:46.300
And so we'll see
here actually sort

00:05:46.300 --> 00:05:49.180
of how ab initio simulation
and, in particular,

00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:53.020
thermodynamic integration has
been used to figure out what

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:55.930
is going on in this region--

00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:57.620
in this region here.

00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:00.430
And as usual, you
need to make sure

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:03.070
that you believe
your energy model.

00:06:03.070 --> 00:06:06.800
So these are a couple
of validation curves.

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:09.710
This is for an HCP iron.

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:12.520
That is one of the
high pressure phases,

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:17.680
and the comparison between the
sort of experimental results

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:19.450
and simulation
where the simulation

00:06:19.450 --> 00:06:20.890
are the sort of solid lines.

00:06:20.890 --> 00:06:23.410
And you see it agrees
very well in describing

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:26.840
the equation of state, pressure
versus volume in this case.

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:29.800
And then in particular,
this is a calculation

00:06:29.800 --> 00:06:34.120
of the phonon modes of
the vibrational frequency.

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:35.950
This is something
that actually you

00:06:35.950 --> 00:06:38.800
could very easily do with
the quantum mechanical tools

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:41.440
that you have done as a
sort of post-processing

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:45.070
of your laboratory three,
but again, it works.

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:45.760
It works.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:46.910
It works very well.

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:49.420
So once you believe
iron, now the issue

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:54.940
is trying to figure out what
is its phase diagram at, say,

00:06:54.940 --> 00:06:57.250
which temperature
you have coexistence

00:06:57.250 --> 00:06:59.050
between the solid
and the liquid.

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:02.320
And you have actually done
this in your laboratory

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:06.640
for a sort of explicit method
to find out the transition

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.850
temperature by just doing
a simulation of a liquid

00:07:09.850 --> 00:07:13.900
and a solid phase, and figuring
out at which temperature

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:15.640
the boundary between
the two phases

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:17.810
doesn't really grow
into each other.

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:19.360
So the solid doesn't
keep growing,

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:21.610
or the liquid
doesn't keep growing.

00:07:21.610 --> 00:07:26.860
And you see an example of
this in sort of what follows.

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:29.680
The caveat that in doing
this kind of simulation

00:07:29.680 --> 00:07:33.610
is that they are still sort of
very expensive to do ab initio.

00:07:33.610 --> 00:07:37.090
You usually need at
least 400 or 500 atoms

00:07:37.090 --> 00:07:39.070
to do such kind of
simulation and sort

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:41.440
of to kill the
final size effects.

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:44.320
And this is, even
now, borderline

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:48.850
for what we can do even
for the simplest elements.

00:07:48.850 --> 00:07:51.970
There is another approach that
I wanted to introduce first,

00:07:51.970 --> 00:07:54.880
and this is the one in which
we actually sort of determine

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:58.010
explicitly the
Gibbs free energy.

00:07:58.010 --> 00:08:01.030
So in this case, what
you want to find out

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:04.120
is thermodynamic stability
at a given pressure

00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:05.780
and at a given temperature.

00:08:05.780 --> 00:08:09.100
So the Gibbs free energy is
your correct thermodynamic

00:08:09.100 --> 00:08:10.220
potential.

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:12.160
And so your goal,
if you want, is

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:15.520
being able to calculate
the Gibbs free energy

00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:18.520
of your solid system as
a function of temperature

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:21.610
and the Gibbs free energy
of your liquid system.

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:25.210
And of course, the point where
these two free energy cross

00:08:25.210 --> 00:08:27.670
is really your
coexistence point.

00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:31.000
Above that critical
temperature, the liquid phase

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:32.440
is more stable.

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:35.230
And below that critical
temperature, the solid--

00:08:35.230 --> 00:08:37.570
that solid phase is more stable.

00:08:37.570 --> 00:08:42.070
And sort of one possible way
of calculating, actually,

00:08:42.070 --> 00:08:46.360
explicitly this free
energy or, in particular,

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:49.270
calculating the free energy
difference with respect

00:08:49.270 --> 00:08:52.570
to a known phase is to use
thermodynamic integration.

00:08:52.570 --> 00:08:55.810
That is a technique that
sort of has been discussed

00:08:55.810 --> 00:08:58.300
in some of the previous
lecture by Professor Ceder,

00:08:58.300 --> 00:09:01.990
so I've just put
up a reminder here.

00:09:01.990 --> 00:09:06.400
And the nomenclature is
that we are using, actually,

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.190
a Hamiltonian or an
energy model that

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:12.040
depends on a parameter lambda.

00:09:12.040 --> 00:09:15.280
And the parameter lambda
is something that, say,

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:18.910
brings us from the solid to the
liquid, because ultimately what

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:21.670
we want to sort of
figure out is, what

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:24.190
is the difference in
Gibbs free energy,

00:09:24.190 --> 00:09:27.040
say, between the
liquid and the solid,

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:29.860
or maybe between two solids,
between one reference

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:33.900
phase of the solid and another
reference phase of the solid?

00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:36.870
And again, the idea behind
thermodynamic integration

00:09:36.870 --> 00:09:40.260
is fairly simple once you
skip all the math here.

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:44.790
Again, one can write out
explicitly the partition,

00:09:44.790 --> 00:09:47.520
or the partition
function is written here.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:51.240
And then it just requires
a little bit of math,

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:54.570
sort of figuring out
that the derivative

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:58.210
of the, in this case,
Gibbs free energy--

00:09:58.210 --> 00:10:00.850
well, sorry, this is
actually a constant volume.

00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:04.970
So it would be a sort of
[? isentropic ?] simulation.

00:10:04.970 --> 00:10:05.820
No, sorry.

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:09.180
It would be constant
volume, constant temperature

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:10.140
simulation.

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:12.600
So [INAUDIBLE] energy.

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:14.820
So the derivative
of the free energy

00:10:14.820 --> 00:10:19.200
with respect to this
parameter lambda--

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:22.470
you see once you sort make the
appropriate substitution-- that

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:27.060
is, you put the logarithm
of the partition function,

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:28.950
and you work out
explicitly what is

00:10:28.950 --> 00:10:31.990
that logarithm of the
partition function in there,

00:10:31.990 --> 00:10:36.225
you have 1 over q times the q
over the lambda, and 1 over q

00:10:36.225 --> 00:10:38.220
is the partition function here.

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:40.830
And this is the derivative
of the partition function

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:41.910
with respect lambda.

00:10:41.910 --> 00:10:45.480
You basically get
an expression that

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:51.210
is nothing else than the average
in your ensemble normalized

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:55.000
by the partition function
of the u over the lambda.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.620
So in order to calculate
what is the derivative

00:10:58.620 --> 00:11:01.740
of the free energy
with respect to lambda,

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:06.000
you need to calculate what
is the thermodynamic average

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.360
in your ensemble of the
derivative of the energy

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:11.640
with respect to lambda.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:15.900
And so this is a quantity
that you can always calculate,

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:20.860
and this is just an
average over your ensemble.

00:11:20.860 --> 00:11:23.050
So let's look at
sort of how this

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:26.150
is done in a specific case.

00:11:26.150 --> 00:11:30.100
So again, I just returned
here the partition function,

00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:31.720
the logarithm--

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:34.390
the free energy, sorry, as
the logarithm of the partition

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:35.620
function.

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:38.620
u will be our internal
energy, and this

00:11:38.620 --> 00:11:43.090
is what you calculate with
your quantum mechanical model.

00:11:43.090 --> 00:11:46.330
And for simplicity,
I've actually

00:11:46.330 --> 00:11:50.050
broken this in three
parts, and that is I've

00:11:50.050 --> 00:11:55.180
written out what is the
energy at the equilibrium

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:59.920
and then the energy for
any possible configuration

00:11:59.920 --> 00:12:03.040
of the ions can be
written as the energy

00:12:03.040 --> 00:12:07.900
at equilibrium plus what is
called the harmonic term.

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:12.310
So when you expand the energy
of a system around equilibrium,

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:15.200
the first derivatives
are 0 by definition.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:18.310
And so here you have
the quadratic terms

00:12:18.310 --> 00:12:20.650
in the displacement
of the position

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:22.210
around that
equilibrium position.

00:12:22.210 --> 00:12:25.780
And then you have all
the nonlinear term that

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:28.360
will call sort of anharmonic.

00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:31.510
And it's actually, say,
in the case of a solid,

00:12:31.510 --> 00:12:33.920
this makes a lot of
sense, because it's

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:38.500
sort of fairly easy to
calculate explicitly

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:43.780
the integral of the partition
function for this term

00:12:43.780 --> 00:12:46.870
in the overall energy function.

00:12:46.870 --> 00:12:48.670
And then this sort
of is reserved

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:53.860
for an explicit integration
than using molecular dynamics.

00:12:53.860 --> 00:12:57.580
And because basically you have
a logarithm of an exponential,

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:00.310
if you sort of break
out of this thing

00:13:00.310 --> 00:13:04.360
in the sum of different
terms, all the terms that

00:13:04.360 --> 00:13:11.060
contribute separate free energy
pieces to your overall system.

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:14.500
And so we could
calculate, let's say,

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:20.410
for a solid system what is
the additional vibrational--

00:13:20.410 --> 00:13:22.210
in this case, free energy--

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:25.510
that comes on top of the
equilibrium ground state

00:13:25.510 --> 00:13:30.040
energy, and coming just
from the harmonic term.

00:13:30.040 --> 00:13:34.090
And I haven't worked out
the algebra explicitly,

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:37.480
but it's actually fairly
easy to do these integrals

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:43.540
by writing the harmonic term in
terms of the interatomic force

00:13:43.540 --> 00:13:44.590
constants.

00:13:44.590 --> 00:13:50.380
So if you sort of figure out
with electronic structure

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:54.070
codes what are the normal
modes of your system--

00:13:54.070 --> 00:13:57.580
that is, what are the
modes that give you

00:13:57.580 --> 00:14:01.240
an expression for the
harmonic term that

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:03.610
is diagonal in the
displacement-- and you find out

00:14:03.610 --> 00:14:05.650
the frequencies,
well, you can actually

00:14:05.650 --> 00:14:10.720
substitute that expression in
here, work out the integral,

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:16.820
and basically what you obtain is
that your harmonic vibrational

00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:24.700
free energy is just given by a
sum over the logarithm of all

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:26.470
your vibrational frequency.

00:14:26.470 --> 00:14:29.890
So this omega here would
be your phonon frequency

00:14:29.890 --> 00:14:33.850
if you go back to what
we had seen before

00:14:33.850 --> 00:14:40.450
for the case of iron when we
have calculated the phonon

00:14:40.450 --> 00:14:41.140
spectrum.

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:42.250
Here it is.

00:14:42.250 --> 00:14:47.680
So here, what we have calculated
is all the possible frequency

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:51.860
for iron, depending
on the wave vector.

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:55.520
So in principle, we have
a continuum of frequency,

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:58.300
and we just need to basically
integrate these curves

00:14:58.300 --> 00:15:03.040
or sum over our course
representation of them

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:05.440
to get the vibrational
free energy--

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:07.810
at least the harmonic term.

00:15:07.810 --> 00:15:08.740
And this is it.

00:15:08.740 --> 00:15:11.500
And so this is sort
of the first step.

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:16.050
This can give me, say,
what is the change

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:19.770
in the vibrational
free energy in going,

00:15:19.770 --> 00:15:22.570
say, from one
phase to the other.

00:15:22.570 --> 00:15:24.960
And I just calculate
the phonon frequency

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:28.020
in sort of two different phases.

00:15:28.020 --> 00:15:32.250
What is more intriguing
is the calculation

00:15:32.250 --> 00:15:35.340
of all the nonlinear
terms that can be very

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:39.210
important at high temperature.

00:15:39.210 --> 00:15:42.780
And this is sort of the
slightly more difficult task,

00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:47.190
because especially in a
sort of ab initio framework,

00:15:47.190 --> 00:15:51.930
it requires very
extensive integration

00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:53.910
of your thermodynamic ensemble.

00:15:53.910 --> 00:15:57.330
So you would do something like
molecular dynamic simulations

00:15:57.330 --> 00:15:59.700
or Monte Carlo
simulation to sample

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:04.470
as much as possible a set of
representative microstates,

00:16:04.470 --> 00:16:08.020
but it tends to
be very expensive.

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:10.920
So there is actually
sort of a very useful,

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:16.920
if you want trick that is often
used in order to calculate

00:16:16.920 --> 00:16:21.540
this anharmonic term, that
remember the anharmonic term is

00:16:21.540 --> 00:16:26.070
nothing else than the overall
vibration of free energy

00:16:26.070 --> 00:16:28.620
minus the harmonic term.

00:16:28.620 --> 00:16:34.800
And the trick are consistently
used in introducing a reference

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:41.220
classical potential so that a
lot of your expensive sampling

00:16:41.220 --> 00:16:45.420
of the phase space can be done
with classical simulations

00:16:45.420 --> 00:16:48.900
and a very expansive ab
initio simulation are only

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:52.530
used to figure out what
is the sort of difference

00:16:52.530 --> 00:16:56.250
in thermodynamical terms
between your quantum

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:58.960
potential and your
classical potential.

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:01.810
So again, sort of just
a mathematical term.

00:17:01.810 --> 00:17:09.510
I mean, we can sort of
think at our overall energy.

00:17:09.510 --> 00:17:13.200
So this would be the
overall, apart from this sort

00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:14.829
of equilibrium term.

00:17:14.829 --> 00:17:17.310
So what we are
trying to calculate

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:20.190
is the difference
between the whole term

00:17:20.190 --> 00:17:22.859
minus the harmonic
term, but we actually

00:17:22.859 --> 00:17:26.609
introduce a classical potential
that sort of hopefully

00:17:26.609 --> 00:17:29.640
reproduces as
closely as possible

00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:33.900
the energies, the interactions
between all our atoms.

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:38.610
And so we can actually break
down this term in two parts--

00:17:38.610 --> 00:17:40.560
one that has to do
with the difference

00:17:40.560 --> 00:17:43.050
between the harmonic crystal
and the reference system,

00:17:43.050 --> 00:17:45.660
and one that has to do with
the difference between sort

00:17:45.660 --> 00:17:50.700
of our overall energy term
here, or the overall free energy

00:17:50.700 --> 00:17:54.870
term, including non-linear
fx minus their reference--

00:17:54.870 --> 00:17:56.610
minus the reference system.

00:17:56.610 --> 00:18:00.360
And now, this here
is a calculation

00:18:00.360 --> 00:18:04.560
that involves only sort of
classical potential calculation

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:05.910
of your phonon frequency.

00:18:05.910 --> 00:18:09.720
So this can be done
very extensively

00:18:09.720 --> 00:18:12.750
over longer classical
simulation, and in a way,

00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:16.830
it captures all the
complexity of the phase space.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:18.660
While this, that
is very expensive,

00:18:18.660 --> 00:18:22.140
because you need to calculate
the internal energy with sort

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:24.720
of the quantum
mechanical model--

00:18:24.720 --> 00:18:28.320
is sort of you are
trying to sample

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:31.500
the difference between
two quantities that

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:33.870
are as similar as possible.

00:18:33.870 --> 00:18:37.770
And in the ideal case in
which your classical potential

00:18:37.770 --> 00:18:41.160
is able actually to reproduce
your quantum potential,

00:18:41.160 --> 00:18:43.140
this goes towards 0.

00:18:43.140 --> 00:18:45.780
So it's something that is
very simple to integrate.

00:18:45.780 --> 00:18:48.030
So by introducing basically
a reference potential,

00:18:48.030 --> 00:18:51.780
you are shifting a lot of
the thermodynamic integration

00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:53.520
to the classical simulation.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:57.030
And you are just using the
quantum mechanical simulations

00:18:57.030 --> 00:18:59.680
to sort of sample
the difference.

00:18:59.680 --> 00:19:01.170
And so this can
be done, actually,

00:19:01.170 --> 00:19:05.520
with much shorter and
much smaller simulations.

00:19:05.520 --> 00:19:08.220
And I want to go actually into
the details of what you need

00:19:08.220 --> 00:19:12.270
to do for the case of iron that
is what is a good potential,

00:19:12.270 --> 00:19:15.480
but people have figured out
that something as simple

00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:17.440
as basically a sort
of Lennard-Jones

00:19:17.440 --> 00:19:21.600
just like kind of potential
on top of anharmonic term

00:19:21.600 --> 00:19:26.980
is actually good enough to
provide a reference potential.

00:19:26.980 --> 00:19:30.090
So basically with
all this formalism,

00:19:30.090 --> 00:19:32.490
what one is able
to do at the end

00:19:32.490 --> 00:19:36.570
is calculate the free
energy differences in which,

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:40.710
if you want the fundamental
components are calculating

00:19:40.710 --> 00:19:43.740
the phonon frequency
of your system--

00:19:43.740 --> 00:19:47.190
in this case, specifically
for the case of a solid--

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:50.250
that gives you the first step
in the vibrational free energy.

00:19:50.250 --> 00:19:53.400
And if nothing else, then
this case, a density function

00:19:53.400 --> 00:19:55.080
or perturbational
theory calculation.

00:19:55.080 --> 00:19:57.060
You want the phonon
spectrum, and then you

00:19:57.060 --> 00:20:00.750
need to do a number of
molecular dynamic simulations

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:04.050
on very large and
sort of very extensive

00:20:04.050 --> 00:20:05.670
for classical potential.

00:20:05.670 --> 00:20:08.400
And then if you want,
you just correct

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:11.710
your classical simulations
with the difference

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:15.370
between the classical and
the quantum potential.

00:20:15.370 --> 00:20:17.460
And once you have
all of data, you

00:20:17.460 --> 00:20:21.780
are basically able to calculate
all sort of the free energies

00:20:21.780 --> 00:20:22.840
that you need.

00:20:22.840 --> 00:20:24.840
And I guess this is an example.

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:27.510
I'll show in a moment
a more telling example

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:30.720
in which, again, sort
of we compare actually

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:34.020
sort of what our prediction
are for the pressure,

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:38.040
volume, curve coming from
the ab initio simulation

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:39.840
and experimental results.

00:20:39.840 --> 00:20:42.060
But more importantly,
if you want,

00:20:42.060 --> 00:20:44.190
we are actually
able to figure out

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:46.290
when the free
energy of the solid

00:20:46.290 --> 00:20:49.020
and the free energy
of the liquid cross.

00:20:49.020 --> 00:20:52.840
And we can do this as
a function of pressure.

00:20:52.840 --> 00:20:57.990
And so this is, at this
stage, our best prediction

00:20:57.990 --> 00:21:02.310
for the phase diagram of iron
as a function of pressure.

00:21:02.310 --> 00:21:04.920
In particular, the
black line here

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:08.820
is sort of the set of
simulation that I've described.

00:21:08.820 --> 00:21:11.220
And there starts to be
a reasonable agreement

00:21:11.220 --> 00:21:13.950
between a number of
Shockley-Gunn experiments

00:21:13.950 --> 00:21:18.120
and a number of simulation that
puts roughly the temperature

00:21:18.120 --> 00:21:23.770
at 330 gigapascal, just
sort of above 6,000 Kelvin.

00:21:23.770 --> 00:21:24.630
And so this was--

00:21:24.630 --> 00:21:27.390
when it came out, the
scientific literature,

00:21:27.390 --> 00:21:30.660
it was sort of hailed as
taking the temperature

00:21:30.660 --> 00:21:32.280
of the core of the Earth.

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:33.840
And at this stage,
it's, again, sort

00:21:33.840 --> 00:21:39.840
of our most accurate prediction
of what is going on inside.

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:44.640
Just sort of to make the point
that this is not the only way,

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:47.790
remember that one can
also do the simulation

00:21:47.790 --> 00:21:49.830
of the coexistence
between the solid

00:21:49.830 --> 00:21:55.560
and the liquid exactly as you
have done in your laboratory,

00:21:55.560 --> 00:21:57.300
in your lab number four.

00:21:57.300 --> 00:22:01.050
This is actually a paper,
again, sort of Science 2000,

00:22:01.050 --> 00:22:05.340
really sort of state
of the art research.

00:22:05.340 --> 00:22:07.550
And in these
particular simulations,

00:22:07.550 --> 00:22:09.730
they used classical potential.

00:22:09.730 --> 00:22:12.050
So again, not very
far from what you

00:22:12.050 --> 00:22:16.010
have done with the only caveat
that the classical potential

00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:19.460
had been extensively
optimized to describe

00:22:19.460 --> 00:22:21.650
solid and liquid iron.

00:22:21.650 --> 00:22:25.960
And the way that
optimization was done,

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:29.420
it used what is called
a force matching

00:22:29.420 --> 00:22:32.660
method, in which
basically you do, again,

00:22:32.660 --> 00:22:37.400
extensive but small ab initio
molecular dynamic simulation.

00:22:37.400 --> 00:22:40.760
And you sort of tune
your classical potential

00:22:40.760 --> 00:22:43.340
in order to have
this more or less

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:46.160
the mean square
error with respect

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:48.050
to the ab initio simulation.

00:22:48.050 --> 00:22:50.180
And that often, because
you have basically so

00:22:50.180 --> 00:22:53.060
many configurations,
and so you sample

00:22:53.060 --> 00:22:56.180
so many possible different
environments for your atoms,

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:59.660
it can somehow give
you a reasonably robust

00:22:59.660 --> 00:23:04.130
classical potentials, again,
in sort of very simple cases.

00:23:04.130 --> 00:23:06.860
This case is just
an elemental system,

00:23:06.860 --> 00:23:12.420
and sort of in a range of
temperature and pressure.

00:23:12.420 --> 00:23:14.720
So this was sort of
an example that I

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:18.500
wanted to discuss a
little bit more in detail.

00:23:18.500 --> 00:23:22.370
I think all this sort of
research area of studying

00:23:22.370 --> 00:23:25.460
the properties of matter
at extreme condition

00:23:25.460 --> 00:23:28.910
has been extremely fruitful from
the point of view of ab initio

00:23:28.910 --> 00:23:30.170
simulations.

00:23:30.170 --> 00:23:33.350
And sort of there
are other cases

00:23:33.350 --> 00:23:39.260
in which actually the phase
diagram of, say, methane

00:23:39.260 --> 00:23:41.630
under high pressure
has sort of led

00:23:41.630 --> 00:23:43.790
to a number of
interesting discoveries.

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:46.880
There are all the planets--

00:23:46.880 --> 00:23:53.820
Jupiter and beyond often are
made by a mixture of methane,

00:23:53.820 --> 00:23:57.290
water, or often, say,
in the case of Jupiter,

00:23:57.290 --> 00:24:00.080
a large amount of hydrogen.

00:24:00.080 --> 00:24:02.810
And the phase diagram of this
system, again, at very high

00:24:02.810 --> 00:24:05.150
pressure is largely unknown.

00:24:05.150 --> 00:24:07.430
One of the most interesting
sort of prediction

00:24:07.430 --> 00:24:10.970
that was made already
in the '30s by Wigner

00:24:10.970 --> 00:24:16.120
was that hydrogen,
under high pressure,

00:24:16.120 --> 00:24:21.130
should really start to behave
as all the other alkali metals

00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:22.060
in the first group.

00:24:22.060 --> 00:24:24.500
If you think
hydrogen is in there,

00:24:24.500 --> 00:24:28.090
and there's a sort of molecular
gas at ambient condition,

00:24:28.090 --> 00:24:30.190
but everything below it--

00:24:30.190 --> 00:24:32.560
it's really a simple metal--

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:36.140
lithium, sodium, potassium,
and so on and so forth.

00:24:36.140 --> 00:24:39.640
And at ambient condition,
hydrogen, if you want,

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:41.890
would belong much
more to group seven

00:24:41.890 --> 00:24:44.740
with the halogens
that really form

00:24:44.740 --> 00:24:49.960
dimer and gases, like a chlorine
or bromine, than on group one.

00:24:49.960 --> 00:24:52.240
But if you keep
compressing, compressing,

00:24:52.240 --> 00:24:56.110
there should be a point in
which it becomes metallic.

00:24:56.110 --> 00:24:58.960
And we haven't really
reached the state.

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:01.480
There are indications from
the shotgun experiments

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:06.970
that it could reach the metallic
state at 350, 400 gigapascal,

00:25:06.970 --> 00:25:09.010
but this is extremely
important, because, say,

00:25:09.010 --> 00:25:11.410
for a planet like
Jupiter, there is

00:25:11.410 --> 00:25:13.330
a huge difference
if we are going

00:25:13.330 --> 00:25:17.890
to have in the inside of the
planet, say, a molecular solid,

00:25:17.890 --> 00:25:21.130
or a metallic solid,
or a metallic fluid.

00:25:21.130 --> 00:25:24.610
If we have a hydrogen that
all of a sudden inside

00:25:24.610 --> 00:25:28.480
is a metallic fluid,
well, we can have there

00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:31.990
right away, like for the case
of Earth, a significant source

00:25:31.990 --> 00:25:35.980
of magnetic field if we start
to have a sort of circulation

00:25:35.980 --> 00:25:37.090
in that fluid.

00:25:37.090 --> 00:25:39.310
So all of this is
very important,

00:25:39.310 --> 00:25:43.380
and I think one of the most
intriguing prediction that

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:46.270
actually sort of
had originally come

00:25:46.270 --> 00:25:50.860
just as a hypothesis
by Martin Ross in 1981

00:25:50.860 --> 00:25:53.290
was that, in some
of this planet,

00:25:53.290 --> 00:25:57.100
there could be an interesting
decomposition of methane.

00:25:57.100 --> 00:25:59.440
So basically, what
could be going on

00:25:59.440 --> 00:26:05.200
is that inside, say, Neptune,
as you increase the pressure,

00:26:05.200 --> 00:26:09.760
your methane molecule under
the effective pressure

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:12.250
starts decomposing.

00:26:12.250 --> 00:26:15.340
And this actually
has been seen in

00:26:15.340 --> 00:26:17.560
quantum mechanical simulations.

00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:20.410
And so what you have
is that-- on one side

00:26:20.410 --> 00:26:23.620
is that the carbon atoms--
and you have a breaking

00:26:23.620 --> 00:26:25.670
of the carbon-hydrogen bond.

00:26:25.670 --> 00:26:31.150
And so you have formation
of pure carbon, of diamonds,

00:26:31.150 --> 00:26:34.480
and you have formation
of higher hydrocarbons.

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:35.950
And actually, there
has always been

00:26:35.950 --> 00:26:38.260
a sort of experimental
observation

00:26:38.260 --> 00:26:41.950
of an anomalous presence
of high order hydrocarbons

00:26:41.950 --> 00:26:44.000
on the surface of this planet.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.330
And so this simulation
for the first time

00:26:46.330 --> 00:26:48.760
provided a reason
why there should

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:51.400
be higher order hydrocarbons.

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:55.330
They are basically created
when methane collapses

00:26:55.330 --> 00:26:59.500
under pressure, and then somehow
from deep inside the planet,

00:26:59.500 --> 00:27:01.570
these sort of
convective currents

00:27:01.570 --> 00:27:03.910
bring these hydrocarbons up.

00:27:03.910 --> 00:27:06.520
But the other prediction
that, I think,

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:09.820
even if not confirmed at the
time is the most appealing,

00:27:09.820 --> 00:27:13.330
is that at the same time you
have nucleation of diamond,

00:27:13.330 --> 00:27:16.990
and so there is this beautiful
picture of basically a rain

00:27:16.990 --> 00:27:20.770
of diamonds taking
place inside the planet

00:27:20.770 --> 00:27:24.320
and basically converging
to the inside.

00:27:24.320 --> 00:27:26.980
And again, this was
just a prediction,

00:27:26.980 --> 00:27:32.680
but I think in 2002 or 2003--
maybe it's mentioned here.

00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:38.530
No, 1999, so just two or three
years after the previous paper,

00:27:38.530 --> 00:27:41.950
finally there were sort of
diamond anvil cell experiments

00:27:41.950 --> 00:27:45.970
made by Raymond
Jeanloz at Berkeley.

00:27:45.970 --> 00:27:50.410
And all of a sudden, methane
under pressure sort of

00:27:50.410 --> 00:27:53.110
gave rise both to
higher hydrocarbons,

00:27:53.110 --> 00:27:55.740
but also to the clear
signature of diamonds.

00:27:55.740 --> 00:27:59.650
So they saw basically the
nucleation of pure diamonds

00:27:59.650 --> 00:28:04.180
just under pressure, and I
guess this brought in general,

00:28:04.180 --> 00:28:08.470
both in the geophysical and in
the planetary community, a lot

00:28:08.470 --> 00:28:12.400
of resonance for the importance
of this ab initio simulation

00:28:12.400 --> 00:28:14.690
in the field.

00:28:14.690 --> 00:28:17.410
And the last example
that I wanted

00:28:17.410 --> 00:28:21.280
to show in terms of sort
of geophysical or planetary

00:28:21.280 --> 00:28:24.070
importance is actually
the one of water

00:28:24.070 --> 00:28:28.540
that, as a very intriguing
phase that was sort of

00:28:28.540 --> 00:28:32.750
suggested for the first
time, again, in 1999--

00:28:32.750 --> 00:28:37.510
and what I'm showing here is
just a network of solid oxygen.

00:28:37.510 --> 00:28:40.510
So here I'm just showing the
oxygen for a high pressure

00:28:40.510 --> 00:28:41.200
phase.

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:43.540
In this simulation,
we were looking

00:28:43.540 --> 00:28:46.660
at 20 gigapascal of pressure.

00:28:46.660 --> 00:28:49.180
And what happens is
that, if you increase

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:52.060
the temperature
enough, actually water

00:28:52.060 --> 00:28:55.720
becomes superprotonic--
that is a very exotic phase.

00:28:55.720 --> 00:28:59.380
So the covalent bonds
between hydrogen and oxygen

00:28:59.380 --> 00:29:04.000
breaks apart, and the
system is still a solid.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:07.180
Again, high pressure even if
there is high temperature,

00:29:07.180 --> 00:29:11.920
but the hydrogens start
moving around like a liquid.

00:29:11.920 --> 00:29:14.350
So you have a
coexistence of phases

00:29:14.350 --> 00:29:17.200
between a solid phase
of one sublattice

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:20.560
and the other sublattice
that has gone liquid.

00:29:20.560 --> 00:29:22.360
There are a number
of sort of materials

00:29:22.360 --> 00:29:25.180
that, even at ordinary
conditions, do this.

00:29:25.180 --> 00:29:29.380
There are some salts silver
iodide that does this,

00:29:29.380 --> 00:29:32.830
and there are interesting
fuel cell materials

00:29:32.830 --> 00:29:35.570
that do this, because,
again, in this case,

00:29:35.570 --> 00:29:38.710
say, when you have a
superprotonic, in this case,

00:29:38.710 --> 00:29:41.770
phase-- that is, when you
have that the protons behave

00:29:41.770 --> 00:29:44.320
as a liquid-- well this
system becomes a very

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:46.900
intriguing ionic conductor.

00:29:46.900 --> 00:29:50.090
But again, this was a
prediction from 1999.

00:29:50.090 --> 00:29:52.330
And actually, just
a few weeks ago

00:29:52.330 --> 00:29:54.820
came the experimental
confirmation

00:29:54.820 --> 00:29:58.750
from Lawrence Livermore,
and lo and behold,

00:29:58.750 --> 00:30:01.970
the superprotonic phase
of water has been found.

00:30:01.970 --> 00:30:05.030
It has been found that 47
gigapascal instead of 20

00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:08.260
gigapascal as usual,
I mean, because of all

00:30:08.260 --> 00:30:11.230
the errors involved in
density function theory,

00:30:11.230 --> 00:30:13.900
and in this specific case,
also, the the errors involved

00:30:13.900 --> 00:30:16.780
with the sort of quantum
mechanical description

00:30:16.780 --> 00:30:19.300
of the vibrational
excitation that, remember,

00:30:19.300 --> 00:30:21.790
is a Bose-Einstein gas.

00:30:21.790 --> 00:30:26.110
And I'll conclude
with the last slide

00:30:26.110 --> 00:30:30.950
that, again, it's not any
more geophysical or planetary,

00:30:30.950 --> 00:30:34.810
but is, again, another very
intriguing example of what

00:30:34.810 --> 00:30:39.160
was discovered in the
high pressure regime.

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:43.060
And this is, again, some
work from the late '90s that

00:30:43.060 --> 00:30:47.560
has to do, actually, with
the behavior of alkali,

00:30:47.560 --> 00:30:51.520
like sodium or lithium
under pressure.

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:56.650
These are metals that we really
sort of describe and consider--

00:30:56.650 --> 00:31:00.340
simple metals, where
the valence electron

00:31:00.340 --> 00:31:04.750
behave as almost nearly
free electron gas.

00:31:04.750 --> 00:31:06.670
Think at lithium for a moment.

00:31:06.670 --> 00:31:10.330
You have a core with two
electron in the 1s orbital,

00:31:10.330 --> 00:31:13.930
and then you have a single
electron on the 2s orbital that

00:31:13.930 --> 00:31:15.910
becomes very delocalized.

00:31:15.910 --> 00:31:18.630
And now this is what was
discovered that, I think,

00:31:18.630 --> 00:31:20.020
it was very appealing.

00:31:20.020 --> 00:31:22.720
And at some level,
it was also confirmed

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:25.330
recently by the
Carnegie group that does

00:31:25.330 --> 00:31:27.640
a lot of these high
pressure experiments,

00:31:27.640 --> 00:31:31.930
but basically, when you start
compressing your system, what

00:31:31.930 --> 00:31:35.560
you have is that the
2s electrons start

00:31:35.560 --> 00:31:37.100
overlapping more and more.

00:31:37.100 --> 00:31:38.800
If you want that
very high pressure,

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:43.990
even the core of your lithium
atoms start overlapping.

00:31:43.990 --> 00:31:47.410
And what's happening
is that Pauli principle

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:49.270
becomes exceedingly relevant.

00:31:49.270 --> 00:31:53.560
That is, you start to
have 2s electrons that,

00:31:53.560 --> 00:31:57.590
by pressure, would be forced to
be almost in the same quantum

00:31:57.590 --> 00:31:58.090
state.

00:31:58.090 --> 00:32:01.000
They start to overlap
very significantly.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:04.780
And what happens is that,
in order to escape this,

00:32:04.780 --> 00:32:07.270
the electrons
actually self localize

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:09.190
in the interstitial position.

00:32:09.190 --> 00:32:12.970
So the 2s electrons, from sort
of being around the lithium

00:32:12.970 --> 00:32:17.170
atom, sort of moves
around and jumps

00:32:17.170 --> 00:32:19.090
into the interstitial position.

00:32:19.090 --> 00:32:23.040
It localizes, and it actually
pairs with another electron.

00:32:23.040 --> 00:32:27.250
So you have that your unit
cell becomes double or sort of

00:32:27.250 --> 00:32:28.720
becomes more complex.

00:32:28.720 --> 00:32:32.260
And actually, your system
is a phase transition

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:37.090
from the metallic case of the
sort of ordinary simple metals

00:32:37.090 --> 00:32:39.850
to an insulating case
in which, actually,

00:32:39.850 --> 00:32:44.230
really a pair of electrons
localize in the interstitials.

00:32:44.230 --> 00:32:47.980
And again, these are actually
sort of cutting edge research

00:32:47.980 --> 00:32:51.160
that one nowadays can
do on a simple computer,

00:32:51.160 --> 00:32:55.090
because studying something
like the equation of state

00:32:55.090 --> 00:32:59.500
of a simple metal in a variety
of [INAUDIBLE] lattices

00:32:59.500 --> 00:33:03.070
and a variety of
crystallographic incarnation

00:33:03.070 --> 00:33:04.990
is actually very simple to do.

00:33:04.990 --> 00:33:06.490
It's nothing different
from what you

00:33:06.490 --> 00:33:09.910
have done for, say, silicon
or the semiconductors

00:33:09.910 --> 00:33:12.040
in your first laboratory.

00:33:12.040 --> 00:33:14.170
With this, I'll
conclude my part,

00:33:14.170 --> 00:33:17.630
and Professor Ceder
will continue from here.

00:33:17.630 --> 00:33:19.480
And again, as a
summary, just wanted

00:33:19.480 --> 00:33:24.100
to give you an example of our
whole line of research that

00:33:24.100 --> 00:33:28.810
has come out from modeling
and very accurate modeling,

00:33:28.810 --> 00:33:33.407
and really going in directions
where experiments would be--

00:33:33.407 --> 00:33:38.410
or still are exceedingly
difficult, or even impossible

00:33:38.410 --> 00:33:40.570
to do.

00:33:40.570 --> 00:33:44.710
And with this, I'll switch
on to the next lecture.

00:33:44.710 --> 00:33:45.630
Let me--

00:33:45.630 --> 00:33:49.570
GERBRAND CEDER: So let me hammer
in again the sort of overview,

00:33:49.570 --> 00:33:53.260
the kind of guideline by
which we set up the course.

00:33:53.260 --> 00:33:56.590
I think by now hopefully
you'll see the structure.

00:33:56.590 --> 00:33:58.120
We covered energy methods.

00:33:58.120 --> 00:34:00.940
We covered simulation
methods, and then

00:34:00.940 --> 00:34:02.810
the last third of
the course was really

00:34:02.810 --> 00:34:07.390
