00:34:09.280 --> 00:34:16.070
how you combine all these things
to make impact on something.

00:34:16.070 --> 00:34:18.830
And this is-- being
at MIT, impact

00:34:18.830 --> 00:34:22.550
is the one thing we
worry a lot about.

00:34:22.550 --> 00:34:25.610
And if you see the
kind of things that--

00:34:25.610 --> 00:34:29.810
to integrate modeling more
with materials research,

00:34:29.810 --> 00:34:32.639
there are really these
four poles that you need.

00:34:32.639 --> 00:34:35.030
There's obviously
method development,

00:34:35.030 --> 00:34:36.739
and we told you
a lot about that.

00:34:36.739 --> 00:34:38.510
We told you what
goes into DFT, what

00:34:38.510 --> 00:34:43.120
goes into molecular
dynamics, Monte Carlo,

00:34:43.120 --> 00:34:46.010
there's an important
factor of dissemination,

00:34:46.010 --> 00:34:48.469
which is getting better
and better done, I think,

00:34:48.469 --> 00:34:49.250
in modeling.

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:51.800
There's now a lot of stuff
where you really just

00:34:51.800 --> 00:34:53.929
can fairly easily
get access to codes.

00:34:53.929 --> 00:34:57.230
You get quantum codes, good MD
codes-- sometimes for money,

00:34:57.230 --> 00:34:59.240
but in many cases, for free.

00:34:59.240 --> 00:35:01.280
And then there's, of
course, the education part,

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:06.380
which we try to address here.

00:35:06.380 --> 00:35:10.780
This is actually a picture from
last year, or two years ago.

00:35:10.780 --> 00:35:15.330
I actually think I have one
from longer ago where, see,

00:35:15.330 --> 00:35:18.572
Professor Marzari still has
a beard, which is how you

00:35:18.572 --> 00:35:19.780
know how old that picture is.

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:23.327
But anyway, but I think,
then, the fourth pole

00:35:23.327 --> 00:35:24.660
is the one you shouldn't forget.

00:35:27.630 --> 00:35:30.000
You think that for modeling
you only need modeling,

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:35.280
but I think what you need more
sometimes than modeling is

00:35:35.280 --> 00:35:37.140
the basic signs of your field.

00:35:37.140 --> 00:35:40.920
I think, without understanding
the field in which you work--

00:35:40.920 --> 00:35:42.960
the theory, the
material science of it--

00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:44.370
there's really
very little impact

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:45.912
you can do with
modeling, because you

00:35:45.912 --> 00:35:48.780
can be a good modeler, but if
you don't know what to model,

00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:50.730
you're never going
to have impact,

00:35:50.730 --> 00:35:53.880
unless you choose to remain
on the pure theory and method

00:35:53.880 --> 00:35:55.030
development side.

00:35:55.030 --> 00:35:59.000
But I would argue that, even
then, you need to understand.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.500
You have to have field specific
knowledge, because otherwise

00:36:01.500 --> 00:36:06.220
you never know what is going
to be important to develop.

00:36:06.220 --> 00:36:10.740
So I sort of hope you
don't forget that.

00:36:10.740 --> 00:36:14.970
So this being the
end of the course,

00:36:14.970 --> 00:36:20.230
I'll give you a few more maybe
sort of loaded perspective--

00:36:20.230 --> 00:36:23.740
personal perspectives on
the field, and what's good,

00:36:23.740 --> 00:36:26.500
and what are the potential
directions about it.

00:36:29.550 --> 00:36:32.330
This is what people
want from you.

00:36:32.330 --> 00:36:34.190
They want properties.

00:36:34.190 --> 00:36:36.230
They want behavior.

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:38.900
And this is where you
essentially start,

00:36:38.900 --> 00:36:41.630
and typically you see people
draw these kind of slides

00:36:41.630 --> 00:36:43.370
of the multi scale perspective.

00:36:43.370 --> 00:36:46.940
You go from atoms to
microstructure to continuum.

00:36:46.940 --> 00:36:50.720
This is essentially--
has almost never worked.

00:36:50.720 --> 00:36:52.830
This is great for raising money.

00:36:52.830 --> 00:36:56.030
It's a great sort of cartoon
view grab of what you do.

00:36:56.030 --> 00:36:59.720
It's rarely that you
actually ever do this.

00:36:59.720 --> 00:37:02.120
There are very few
properties where you make it

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:04.760
across all the length scales.

00:37:04.760 --> 00:37:12.000
And so what you really do is you
kind of connect at some level.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:13.880
You sort of connect
these through your brain.

00:37:13.880 --> 00:37:16.670
In many cases,
there are properties

00:37:16.670 --> 00:37:21.140
we determine just by doing
stuff at the electronic level.

00:37:21.140 --> 00:37:24.110
And we don't barter
coarse-graining that explicitly

00:37:24.110 --> 00:37:25.407
through the length scales.

00:37:25.407 --> 00:37:26.990
And what you're
really doing is you're

00:37:26.990 --> 00:37:30.840
using your basic materials
theory knowledge-- for example,

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:36.530
that maybe when you work
on color of materials.

00:37:36.530 --> 00:37:39.380
I mean, I had this one--
jewelers once came to me

00:37:39.380 --> 00:37:41.690
and asked if I
could predict color

00:37:41.690 --> 00:37:47.090
for gemstones and for thin
layer-- thin surface layers

00:37:47.090 --> 00:37:49.050
that they could use to coat.

00:37:49.050 --> 00:37:52.540
So in many cases, those are
fairly local properties,

00:37:52.540 --> 00:37:54.510
especially in oxides.

00:37:54.510 --> 00:37:57.720
So there you sort of decide
yourself, gee, there's

00:37:57.720 --> 00:37:59.910
kind of one length
scale that's important--

00:37:59.910 --> 00:38:03.310
this one-- and I'm going to
directly calculate my property.

00:38:03.310 --> 00:38:06.520
So this is you.

00:38:06.520 --> 00:38:09.010
This is, I think, why your
field specific knowledge is,

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:13.810
in some sense, more important
than all these multi scale

00:38:13.810 --> 00:38:16.560
techniques.

00:38:16.560 --> 00:38:21.830
This is my pet topic that--

00:38:21.830 --> 00:38:25.750
it may seem obvious
that you can--

00:38:25.750 --> 00:38:28.310
an obvious goal to try
to simulate all the way

00:38:28.310 --> 00:38:31.120
from electrons to properties
by coarse-graining the length

00:38:31.120 --> 00:38:31.650
scale.

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:34.670
But you have so much more
impact if you just substitute

00:38:34.670 --> 00:38:37.670
that idea by knowledge.

00:38:37.670 --> 00:38:39.260
I think, if all
the money had been

00:38:39.260 --> 00:38:42.410
spent on trying to integrate
length scale had been spent

00:38:42.410 --> 00:38:44.810
on actually trying to
integrate materials

00:38:44.810 --> 00:38:48.950
modeling with material science
by connecting your field

00:38:48.950 --> 00:38:52.020
specific knowledge, by trying
to figure out what to compute,

00:38:52.020 --> 00:38:57.720
which is often the hard part,
we'd actually done much better.

00:38:57.720 --> 00:39:03.570
So I'm going to give you an
example, which I really like.

00:39:03.570 --> 00:39:04.580
It's not my work.

00:39:04.580 --> 00:39:07.040
It's done by people
at Northwestern.

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:10.505
It's on intergranular
embrittlement of iron.

00:39:10.505 --> 00:39:12.130
And this is sort of
one of these things

00:39:12.130 --> 00:39:14.350
that you really think
you need a multi scale

00:39:14.350 --> 00:39:17.700
sort of big kind of
modeling approach on.

00:39:17.700 --> 00:39:20.590
Essentially, the
observation is that there's

00:39:20.590 --> 00:39:23.740
quite a few impurities in
steel that embrittle steel,

00:39:23.740 --> 00:39:28.220
and there's some that actually
enhance the internal cohesion.

00:39:28.220 --> 00:39:31.120
Sort of the typical
examples are phosphorous,

00:39:31.120 --> 00:39:32.110
which is really bad.

00:39:32.110 --> 00:39:34.780
Phosphorus is a really bad
embrittler of high strength

00:39:34.780 --> 00:39:39.910
steel, whereas boron tends to
enhance intergranular cohesion.

00:39:39.910 --> 00:39:42.650
So when you sort of hear
about this for the first time,

00:39:42.650 --> 00:39:44.750
you think, well, how am
I going to study this?

00:39:44.750 --> 00:39:48.340
Maybe I'll set up a big
simulation with a grain

00:39:48.340 --> 00:39:50.920
boundary in, and I'll
put phosphorus there,

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:53.770
or I'll put born there, and
I'll try to pull it apart.

00:39:53.770 --> 00:39:57.190
And that'd sort of be
the brute force, maybe

00:39:57.190 --> 00:39:58.360
multiscale approach.

00:39:58.360 --> 00:40:01.550
You could embed that
in a continuum theory,

00:40:01.550 --> 00:40:03.910
but there's a sort
of very simpler--

00:40:03.910 --> 00:40:05.920
a very basic theory
that tells you there's

00:40:05.920 --> 00:40:07.970
a much simpler way
to understand this.

00:40:07.970 --> 00:40:10.810
And that's the Rice-Wang
theory, which essentially

00:40:10.810 --> 00:40:14.770
states that the embrittling
tendency of a solute

00:40:14.770 --> 00:40:17.170
depends on the
difference in segregation

00:40:17.170 --> 00:40:20.110
energy between the segregation
energy for that element

00:40:20.110 --> 00:40:23.810
to a grain boundary
and to a free surface.

00:40:23.810 --> 00:40:26.150
And you can sort of
intuitively-- this is actually

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:27.420
mathematically justified.

00:40:27.420 --> 00:40:29.060
It's actually a quite
elaborate theory

00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:32.750
that you can catch
in two sentences,

00:40:32.750 --> 00:40:36.020
but you can sort of see why this
is true from a driving force

00:40:36.020 --> 00:40:37.340
perspective.

00:40:37.340 --> 00:40:40.670
If you have an impurity
that has a large segregation

00:40:40.670 --> 00:40:44.390
energy to a surface rather
than a grain boundary,

00:40:44.390 --> 00:40:47.588
then its presence is
going to enhance surfaces,

00:40:47.588 --> 00:40:49.130
because then it can
have that benefit

00:40:49.130 --> 00:40:52.230
from that large
segregation energy.

00:40:52.230 --> 00:40:55.430
So those are going to be
embrittlers, because they will

00:40:55.430 --> 00:40:57.650
tend to promote decohesion.

00:40:57.650 --> 00:41:00.060
Whereas the ones that have
a very large segregation

00:41:00.060 --> 00:41:02.870
energy at the grain boundary,
rather than the free surface,

00:41:02.870 --> 00:41:06.210
will tend to promote cohesion.

00:41:06.210 --> 00:41:08.270
And so if you believe
Rice-Wang theory,

00:41:08.270 --> 00:41:09.780
then this problem
is very simple.

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:13.410
All you have to do is
calculate segregation energies,

00:41:13.410 --> 00:41:15.070
and that you can do.

00:41:15.070 --> 00:41:17.580
See, now you're back
to the atomistic level.

00:41:17.580 --> 00:41:20.190
You could set up a supercell
with a grain boundary

00:41:20.190 --> 00:41:22.790
and really calculate
the energy there.

00:41:22.790 --> 00:41:24.540
Do the same on the
surface, and you really

00:41:24.540 --> 00:41:26.865
don't have to do any dynamics.

00:41:31.977 --> 00:41:33.310
And that's what these folks did.

00:41:33.310 --> 00:41:34.320
This is our work.

00:41:34.320 --> 00:41:37.240
This is work that was published
in Science about 10 years ago

00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:41.020
and already by Art Freeman's
group and Greg Olsen, who

00:41:41.020 --> 00:41:44.200
sort of runs a company that
does atomistic modeling

00:41:44.200 --> 00:41:47.200
and other modeling
for steel development.

00:41:47.200 --> 00:41:51.490
And essentially, you see
that this theory works out

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:52.870
very well.

00:41:52.870 --> 00:41:57.760
On one side, you have the
strong embrittlers, phosphorus

00:41:57.760 --> 00:41:58.480
and sulfur.

00:41:58.480 --> 00:42:00.740
And they essentially
have much higher--

00:42:00.740 --> 00:42:03.070
this is the difference
in segregation energy

00:42:03.070 --> 00:42:06.550
between the surface
and the grain boundary.

00:42:06.550 --> 00:42:10.490
These very much want to
segregate to the surface.

00:42:10.490 --> 00:42:13.390
And that's why they tend to
create internal surfaces,

00:42:13.390 --> 00:42:16.150
whereas carbon, to
a lesser extent,

00:42:16.150 --> 00:42:19.720
but boron to a large
extent promotes decohesion.

00:42:19.720 --> 00:42:22.990
So you can get a fairly
easily good insight

00:42:22.990 --> 00:42:27.730
of what are embrittlers
without having to coarse-grain

00:42:27.730 --> 00:42:31.856
across all the length scales.

00:42:31.856 --> 00:42:35.017
AUDIENCE: Why is the
separation different?

00:42:35.017 --> 00:42:36.100
GERBRAND CEDER: I'm sorry?

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:39.284
AUDIENCE: Why is the separation
different in both boron

00:42:39.284 --> 00:42:42.480
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:42.480 --> 00:42:45.420
GERBRAND CEDER: Yeah,
why it's different.

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:48.450
That's actually what that paper
is about, why it's different,

00:42:48.450 --> 00:42:49.590
essentially.

00:42:49.590 --> 00:42:51.910
And I don't remember
anymore, but I know

00:42:51.910 --> 00:42:53.160
it had to do with the bonding.

00:42:53.160 --> 00:42:55.560
This is why these
pictures are here.

00:42:55.560 --> 00:42:59.130
There's a very-- I think it
probably has to do with the--

00:42:59.130 --> 00:43:01.080
well, first of all,
boron is smaller.

00:43:01.080 --> 00:43:04.170
There's definitely a size
effect, boron and carbon.

00:43:04.170 --> 00:43:07.470
These two are much
smaller than these two,

00:43:07.470 --> 00:43:09.450
but there's another
effect, I think,

00:43:09.450 --> 00:43:11.910
which has to do with their--

00:43:11.910 --> 00:43:14.970
these, I think, tend to prefer--

00:43:14.970 --> 00:43:19.020
in some sense, have much
more bonding potency.

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:21.540
So in a grain boundary,
they have a lot--

00:43:21.540 --> 00:43:23.460
they have higher coordination.

00:43:23.460 --> 00:43:26.370
So they gain a lot more
from covalent bonding

00:43:26.370 --> 00:43:28.100
than these two.

00:43:28.100 --> 00:43:29.850
So these two don't
gain as much from being

00:43:29.850 --> 00:43:32.010
coordinated by iron atoms.

00:43:32.010 --> 00:43:34.690
I think that's what I seem
to remember, the gist of it.

00:43:34.690 --> 00:43:37.110
But that's exactly what
that paper is about.

00:43:42.770 --> 00:43:46.357
To sort of end, I wanted
to mention one thing

00:43:46.357 --> 00:43:48.440
that we actually haven't
talked about that I think

00:43:48.440 --> 00:43:50.150
that is becoming
a fairly big issue

00:43:50.150 --> 00:43:53.750
in computational modeling.

00:43:53.750 --> 00:43:57.200
There's sort of
two ways that I've

00:43:57.200 --> 00:43:59.750
mentioned to go from all
this stuff you can calculate

00:43:59.750 --> 00:44:02.960
at the atomistic and electronic
level to the macroscopic level.

00:44:02.960 --> 00:44:04.520
One is to just sort
of think your way

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:07.303
through it, what's important,
and I'll just calculate that.

00:44:07.303 --> 00:44:09.470
And then one is to sort of
do this sort of much more

00:44:09.470 --> 00:44:13.640
explicit coarse-graining or
simply handing off information.

00:44:13.640 --> 00:44:15.980
With diffusion, you can
just hand off information.

00:44:15.980 --> 00:44:18.140
You can calculate
activation barriers.

00:44:18.140 --> 00:44:19.910
You can put that in
a kinetic Monte Carlo

00:44:19.910 --> 00:44:21.140
to get diffusivities.

00:44:21.140 --> 00:44:24.380
And then you can hand that off
to macroscopic diffusion theory

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:26.120
and do simulations.

00:44:26.120 --> 00:44:28.820
There's really a third
one that's emerging,

00:44:28.820 --> 00:44:31.130
and that's sort of
essentially giving up

00:44:31.130 --> 00:44:33.980
on trying to
understand the relation

00:44:33.980 --> 00:44:36.740
between macroscopic
and microscopic,

00:44:36.740 --> 00:44:40.410
but rather try to
determine it statistically.

00:44:40.410 --> 00:44:43.120
And this has been done in
chemistry for a long time.

00:44:43.120 --> 00:44:47.580
It's really only now, I think,
reaching material science.

00:44:47.580 --> 00:44:49.530
Chemists have used
things like QSAR,

00:44:49.530 --> 00:44:52.911
which are a quantum structure--

00:44:52.911 --> 00:44:57.130
and I forget what the A
is-- relations or something.

00:44:57.130 --> 00:45:01.515
But essentially, their
idea is that maybe there

00:45:01.515 --> 00:45:03.140
are certain macroscopic
properties that

00:45:03.140 --> 00:45:06.770
are so hard to link to the
electronic structure-- that is,

00:45:06.770 --> 00:45:09.680
you just try to correlate them.

00:45:09.680 --> 00:45:11.190
And I'll give you an idea--

00:45:11.190 --> 00:45:12.553
an example.

00:45:12.553 --> 00:45:13.970
One where this is
done extensively

00:45:13.970 --> 00:45:17.130
is toxicity of molecules.

00:45:17.130 --> 00:45:21.800
How do you predict
toxicity of molecules?

00:45:21.800 --> 00:45:23.700
This is a very
difficult question.

00:45:23.700 --> 00:45:25.190
I mean, how do chemists do it?

00:45:25.190 --> 00:45:28.070
Well, gee, they got a lot
of experience, essentially.

00:45:28.070 --> 00:45:34.360
All these groups probably react
with this part of your body,

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:37.222
but how do you even
coarse-grain towards toxicity.

00:45:37.222 --> 00:45:38.680
It's essentially,
what is toxicity?

00:45:38.680 --> 00:45:43.690
It's the reactivity would have
an enormous large potential

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:47.990
of molecules, what your
molecule can do with it.

00:45:47.990 --> 00:45:49.870
So people have tried
to do that with QSARs.

00:45:49.870 --> 00:45:52.930
Essentially what they say
is, for a lot of molecules

00:45:52.930 --> 00:45:56.110
for which I know that they're
either toxic or not toxic,

00:45:56.110 --> 00:45:58.990
I'm going to calculate
with quantum mechanics,

00:45:58.990 --> 00:46:02.830
as much as I can, bond
lengths, electron densities,

00:46:02.830 --> 00:46:04.360
electron negativities.

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:06.700
I mean, people literally
have parameterized

00:46:06.700 --> 00:46:09.940
charged density
surfaces for molecules.

00:46:09.940 --> 00:46:11.680
And then they do a
correlation study.

00:46:11.680 --> 00:46:14.590
They do something like
principal component analysis

00:46:14.590 --> 00:46:16.180
or linear regression,
and they see

00:46:16.180 --> 00:46:19.150
which factors at
the atomic scale

00:46:19.150 --> 00:46:21.980
correlate most to the output.

00:46:21.980 --> 00:46:24.950
And there are powerful
data mining techniques

00:46:24.950 --> 00:46:26.150
that do exactly this.

00:46:26.150 --> 00:46:27.890
This is where the
field of science

00:46:27.890 --> 00:46:30.470
really intersects with
a lot of other fields.

00:46:30.470 --> 00:46:34.010
When you apply
for a credit card,

00:46:34.010 --> 00:46:36.320
the first thing that people
do on the information you

00:46:36.320 --> 00:46:38.900
provide-- that the companies
do is they data mine you,

00:46:38.900 --> 00:46:42.330
and they predict essentially
your risk of default.

00:46:42.330 --> 00:46:46.430
And that's all done with
correlation studies.

00:46:46.430 --> 00:46:48.410
They have enormous
large databases

00:46:48.410 --> 00:46:50.060
of people who have
been in default,

00:46:50.060 --> 00:46:52.850
and they know that, well,
if you're 23 years old

00:46:52.850 --> 00:46:55.917
you're probably more likely to
default than when you're 47.

00:46:55.917 --> 00:46:57.500
And so all that comes
out of the data.

00:46:57.500 --> 00:46:58.730
And people have
essentially tried

00:46:58.730 --> 00:47:00.320
to do the same thing
with the relation

00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:03.458
between macroscopic behavior
and electronic structure.

00:47:03.458 --> 00:47:05.750
And in chemistry, it's very
well advanced, I would say.

00:47:05.750 --> 00:47:07.530
You can buy QSAR software.

00:47:07.530 --> 00:47:08.990
You do a search on Google.

00:47:08.990 --> 00:47:11.000
You'll find it everywhere.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.830
In sort of solid
condensed matter,

00:47:13.830 --> 00:47:15.860
it's really sort
of in its infancy,

00:47:15.860 --> 00:47:17.640
but you're starting to see it.

00:47:17.640 --> 00:47:19.860
And one of the reasons I
think it's in its infancy,

00:47:19.860 --> 00:47:21.980
it's harder--

00:47:21.980 --> 00:47:23.540
the link between
those properties

00:47:23.540 --> 00:47:26.660
and electronic
structure is harder.

00:47:26.660 --> 00:47:31.430
There are intermediate scales
which can mess up the relation.

00:47:31.430 --> 00:47:33.470
This would never be
successful probably

00:47:33.470 --> 00:47:36.140
for mechanical
properties because we

00:47:36.140 --> 00:47:38.030
know that things that--

00:47:38.030 --> 00:47:40.340
two materials that
look almost identical

00:47:40.340 --> 00:47:41.990
on the microscopic
scale can have

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:43.880
very different
mechanical behavior

00:47:43.880 --> 00:47:45.980
depending on the
impurity level, depending

00:47:45.980 --> 00:47:47.570
on the microstructure.

00:47:47.570 --> 00:47:49.940
So you kind of already
know ahead of time

00:47:49.940 --> 00:47:51.770
you're lost if you
try to correlate just

00:47:51.770 --> 00:47:56.853
to atomistic properties, but
it may work for other cases.

00:47:56.853 --> 00:47:58.520
The other thing that
makes this possible

00:47:58.520 --> 00:48:01.100
is that essentially we get
enormous amounts of computing

00:48:01.100 --> 00:48:05.000
power, and we can do very high
throughput data generation

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:05.990
at the atomistic level.

00:48:05.990 --> 00:48:07.865
And I was going to show
you just one example.

00:48:12.440 --> 00:48:15.940
So this is the idea that
you essentially correlate

00:48:15.940 --> 00:48:19.025
these things, but let
me skip through that--

00:48:19.025 --> 00:48:22.410
that you use some
kind of learning

00:48:22.410 --> 00:48:25.650
method like neural networks,
or Bayesian statistics,

00:48:25.650 --> 00:48:28.230
or some kind of
correlation method

00:48:28.230 --> 00:48:34.330
to correlate output
to calculable input.

00:48:34.330 --> 00:48:37.830
So let me show you one example.

00:48:37.830 --> 00:48:40.260
This is something I
had gotten into myself,

00:48:40.260 --> 00:48:44.250
and still I mean
since a few years--

00:48:44.250 --> 00:48:46.440
sort of a very old
problem, and it

00:48:46.440 --> 00:48:48.900
was essentially
trying to predict

00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:50.947
crystal structure of materials.

00:48:50.947 --> 00:48:52.530
It's a really old
premise, essentially

00:48:52.530 --> 00:48:55.290
an unsolved problem, and
it's an intriguing one,

00:48:55.290 --> 00:48:58.920
because you can actually
show quite dramatically

00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:01.440
that the energetics of
quantum mechanics, the way we

00:49:01.440 --> 00:49:03.270
do it in our density
functional theory--

00:49:03.270 --> 00:49:06.330
is actually pretty much most
of the time accurate enough

00:49:06.330 --> 00:49:10.030
to predict the stable
crystal structure.

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:11.790
So what do I mean with predict?

00:49:11.790 --> 00:49:14.580
What it means is
that the true crystal

00:49:14.580 --> 00:49:16.550
structure will have
the lowest energy,

00:49:16.550 --> 00:49:19.440
but the problem is finding it.

00:49:19.440 --> 00:49:22.260
So what I'm saying is, if
I gave you a list of 20

00:49:22.260 --> 00:49:24.570
and I say the winner
is among here,

00:49:24.570 --> 00:49:27.030
you're done, because you
calculate the energy of all 20.

00:49:27.030 --> 00:49:28.710
And the lowest one
will be the real one,

00:49:28.710 --> 00:49:30.510
but you can't make
that list of 20.

00:49:30.510 --> 00:49:31.710
That's the problem.

00:49:31.710 --> 00:49:33.000
It's a search problem.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.340
It's an optimization
problem, rather than

00:49:35.340 --> 00:49:37.910
a sort of energy problem.

00:49:37.910 --> 00:49:41.760
So the idea we have
is that, rather

00:49:41.760 --> 00:49:45.360
than trying to calculate
the energy of all crystal

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:50.100
structures, can you guess
them by calculating a few

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:54.510
and correlating their relation
with a whole lot of other ones?

00:49:54.510 --> 00:49:55.750
So it's the same idea.

00:49:55.750 --> 00:49:58.140
Let's say you have
a really big vector.

00:49:58.140 --> 00:50:00.895
This is like the energy
of all possible crystal

00:50:00.895 --> 00:50:02.020
structures, whatever it is.

00:50:02.020 --> 00:50:04.440
In the end, we have to use
finite numbers, you'll see.

00:50:04.440 --> 00:50:08.520
But can I just calculate
a few that goes fast--

00:50:08.520 --> 00:50:09.720
that's the one in blue--

00:50:09.720 --> 00:50:12.240
and then predict
all the ones in red

00:50:12.240 --> 00:50:15.390
without calculating
them so that I get

00:50:15.390 --> 00:50:17.700
to sort of a complete vector?

00:50:17.700 --> 00:50:21.708
And the way you want to do
this is by correlation methods.

00:50:21.708 --> 00:50:23.250
The philosophical
question is really,

00:50:23.250 --> 00:50:27.540
if you calculate a few pieces
of energetics of materials,

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:29.850
do you have enough
information in there

00:50:29.850 --> 00:50:32.790
to say a lot more
about the material?

00:50:32.790 --> 00:50:34.467
And you can do that explicitly.

00:50:34.467 --> 00:50:36.300
Some people would say
I'm going to calculate

00:50:36.300 --> 00:50:39.397
a few pieces of energetics--
fit potentials to it, say.

00:50:39.397 --> 00:50:41.730
And then with those potentials,
calculate a large amount

00:50:41.730 --> 00:50:42.450
of other things.

00:50:42.450 --> 00:50:44.183
That's the explicit approach.

00:50:44.183 --> 00:50:45.600
The question you
can ask yourself,

00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:48.090
can you do this implicitly?

00:50:48.090 --> 00:50:50.880
And that's what we did
by building correlations.

00:50:50.880 --> 00:50:54.450
Essentially, we build a
sort of a smart algorithm--

00:50:54.450 --> 00:50:57.030
call it a neural net or
whatever-- that essentially

00:50:57.030 --> 00:50:58.690
builds this relation.

00:50:58.690 --> 00:51:01.290
So you train it on large
amounts of data sets

00:51:01.290 --> 00:51:03.340
for which you have
the full vector.

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:04.840
Essentially, you're
asking yourself,

00:51:04.840 --> 00:51:08.580
is there a correlation
between the pink data

00:51:08.580 --> 00:51:10.740
variables and the blue ones?

00:51:10.740 --> 00:51:12.990
And it turns out that there is.

00:51:17.390 --> 00:51:18.440
Gee, OK.

00:51:18.440 --> 00:51:21.950
Well, this is the
picture I forgot.

00:51:21.950 --> 00:51:24.980
You can actually, with
a few calculations,

00:51:24.980 --> 00:51:29.310
predict very well the
energy of other things.

00:51:29.310 --> 00:51:32.420
And this is sort of the summary.

00:51:32.420 --> 00:51:35.960
This is out of a very large
collection of binary metals

00:51:35.960 --> 00:51:39.050
where we did the test,
and this is essentially

00:51:39.050 --> 00:51:41.060
out of how many
calculations do you

00:51:41.060 --> 00:51:44.570
need to do to get all the
ground structures in the system

00:51:44.570 --> 00:51:46.540
with a given accuracy?

00:51:46.540 --> 00:51:48.560
Because of course, this
is a statistical method,

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:53.590
so you're never going to get
100% accuracy, unless you

00:51:53.590 --> 00:51:55.120
calculate everything.

00:51:55.120 --> 00:51:59.560
But what you see is that with
something like 15 calculations,

00:51:59.560 --> 00:52:02.890
you get 85% to 90%
accuracy with--

00:52:02.890 --> 00:52:05.300
this is with the data
mining technique.

00:52:05.300 --> 00:52:10.210
So this is an example of you
build a predictive method

00:52:10.210 --> 00:52:15.840
without a theory, purely
based on statistics.

00:52:15.840 --> 00:52:19.050
And you see more and
more of that done.

00:52:19.050 --> 00:52:22.170
There are people who
built correlation methods

00:52:22.170 --> 00:52:26.700
between very basic electronic
structure input data

00:52:26.700 --> 00:52:29.850
and finite temperature
data-- for example,

00:52:29.850 --> 00:52:34.040
like melting point, which
I think, as you've seen,

00:52:34.040 --> 00:52:36.407
is a non-trivial thing
to actually calculate,

00:52:36.407 --> 00:52:37.990
because melting point
you sort of need

00:52:37.990 --> 00:52:41.790
the intersection of the liquid
and the bulk free energy.

00:52:41.790 --> 00:52:46.750
So you could argue, how is that
melting point already hidden

00:52:46.750 --> 00:52:49.962
in the energetics, and can
I extract that correlation?

00:52:52.580 --> 00:52:55.910
So I'm going to skip
through a bunch of slides

00:52:55.910 --> 00:52:58.490
because I want to
give you enough time

00:52:58.490 --> 00:53:01.220
to do the evaluations.

00:53:01.220 --> 00:53:04.530
These were actually slides on
examples of materials design.

00:53:04.530 --> 00:53:06.440
Well, maybe I should--
a few more minutes--

00:53:06.440 --> 00:53:08.240
say a few things about it.

00:53:08.240 --> 00:53:10.820
One was band gap engineering.

00:53:10.820 --> 00:53:13.910
The reason I put it in there
is because bandgap is the one

00:53:13.910 --> 00:53:15.440
thing people always
think with DFT,

00:53:15.440 --> 00:53:17.030
well, I can't do
anything useful.

00:53:17.030 --> 00:53:20.060
The bandgap is always like
a factor of 2, sometimes

00:53:20.060 --> 00:53:21.420
more off.

00:53:21.420 --> 00:53:23.390
But you can correct for that.

00:53:23.390 --> 00:53:25.870
People have made
empirical pseudopotentials

00:53:25.870 --> 00:53:26.780
that correct for it.

00:53:26.780 --> 00:53:28.400
There are actually
now methods out

00:53:28.400 --> 00:53:32.550
there that will give you
the bandgap more accurately.

00:53:32.550 --> 00:53:35.960
But the whole idea
is that you still

00:53:35.960 --> 00:53:38.660
get a fairly systematic
ordering of the bandgaps,

00:53:38.660 --> 00:53:41.870
and you look at-- can look
at bunches of semiconductors.

00:53:41.870 --> 00:53:43.730
And what I want
to show you here--

00:53:43.730 --> 00:53:46.340
this was actually a
Monte Carlo optimization

00:53:46.340 --> 00:53:48.680
of the bandgap of
super lattices.

00:53:48.680 --> 00:53:52.070
These were aluminum gallium
arsenide super lattices,

00:53:52.070 --> 00:53:57.560
and essentially the
configuration space

00:53:57.560 --> 00:54:00.740
over which they
searched was, how do you

00:54:00.740 --> 00:54:02.540
arrange the aluminum
and the gallium

00:54:02.540 --> 00:54:04.430
on the cation sublattice?

00:54:04.430 --> 00:54:08.360
And so essentially
this was a scheme--

00:54:08.360 --> 00:54:10.280
a Monte Carlo
scheme to sort of go

00:54:10.280 --> 00:54:14.590
to the largest possible
bandgap in that system.

00:54:14.590 --> 00:54:18.140
So it's a fairly well known
example of materials designed

00:54:18.140 --> 00:54:20.870
purely by computation,
and you find

00:54:20.870 --> 00:54:23.030
that, after about 10,000
Monte Carlo moves,

00:54:23.030 --> 00:54:28.190
you seem to find pretty much
what the maximal bandgap is

00:54:28.190 --> 00:54:29.210
in that system.

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:32.030
And then you can try to
make that will then be--

00:54:32.030 --> 00:54:34.080
a thermoelectric is
one where there's

00:54:34.080 --> 00:54:38.300
been several ab initio
predictions for very high

00:54:38.300 --> 00:54:39.440
thermoelectric coefficient.

00:54:39.440 --> 00:54:45.450
Then I'll show you one was
this lanthanum antimony,

00:54:45.450 --> 00:54:46.555
essentially.

00:54:51.670 --> 00:54:54.790
So my last two slides are
on the future of modeling.

00:54:54.790 --> 00:54:58.400
I can't imagine a
better feel to be in.

00:54:58.400 --> 00:55:01.750
And I think there's a few
reasons of-- the two things

00:55:01.750 --> 00:55:04.060
that we essentially
benefit from tremendously--

00:55:04.060 --> 00:55:07.480
one is computing power.

00:55:07.480 --> 00:55:10.330
I mean, when I started in
this field in the early '90s,

00:55:10.330 --> 00:55:13.030
I mean, I can't even
thinking back anymore

00:55:13.030 --> 00:55:14.980
how slow and expensive
computers were.

00:55:14.980 --> 00:55:18.350
And that's a good 10 years ago.

00:55:18.350 --> 00:55:22.690
So we ride this curve
with an anomalous benefit.

00:55:22.690 --> 00:55:25.780
In my department talks,
I usually show numbers.

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:27.670
I think, in the last
20 years, you've

00:55:27.670 --> 00:55:29.830
had an improvement of
sort of performance

00:55:29.830 --> 00:55:34.876
versus price of something
like 10 to 50 million.

00:55:34.876 --> 00:55:37.510
That's how much more computing
power you get for your buck

00:55:37.510 --> 00:55:40.653
now than actually
about 15, 20 years ago.

00:55:40.653 --> 00:55:41.320
That's enormous.

00:55:41.320 --> 00:55:43.362
There are no other techniques
in material science

00:55:43.362 --> 00:55:45.020
that do that, period.

00:55:45.020 --> 00:55:47.000
So you ride this enormous curve.

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:48.760
And for whatever
people say, this

00:55:48.760 --> 00:55:51.970
is likely to continue at
least for quite a while.

00:55:51.970 --> 00:55:54.430
I think another one is that
we benefit tremendously

00:55:54.430 --> 00:55:57.310
from all the developments
in condensed matter theory,

00:55:57.310 --> 00:55:59.620
because this allows
us to compute.

00:55:59.620 --> 00:56:02.650
Those allow us-- the
benefits in condensed matter

00:56:02.650 --> 00:56:05.860
theory allow us to compute
things much more accurately.

00:56:05.860 --> 00:56:09.490
And the third leg is the basic
materials theory development,

00:56:09.490 --> 00:56:10.990
which is probably
the sort of weaker

00:56:10.990 --> 00:56:13.570
leg of the three-legged stool.

00:56:13.570 --> 00:56:16.750
But so this is
one of the reasons

00:56:16.750 --> 00:56:20.030
this field is still very good.

00:56:20.030 --> 00:56:22.150
You should keep into
account scaling,

00:56:22.150 --> 00:56:26.250
which we've only sort of
cursorily said something about.

00:56:26.250 --> 00:56:29.410
But here's some examples of
why scaling can kill you.

00:56:32.440 --> 00:56:35.380
I put out some
hypothetical examples

00:56:35.380 --> 00:56:40.630
of linear scaling examples, cube
scaling examples, and worse.

00:56:40.630 --> 00:56:43.060
If you take an example
of linear scaling,

00:56:43.060 --> 00:56:46.960
I think molecular dynamics
with real space potentials

00:56:46.960 --> 00:56:48.940
is probably pretty well
up to linear scaling

00:56:48.940 --> 00:56:51.610
these days, because you
can partition space.

00:56:51.610 --> 00:56:53.620
As soon as you start
partitioning space

00:56:53.620 --> 00:56:55.120
with finite range
potential, you can

00:56:55.120 --> 00:56:58.120
get basically linear scaling.

00:56:58.120 --> 00:57:01.680
So I figured out, what
can you do in 40 years,

00:57:01.680 --> 00:57:04.320
assuming we get about a
factor of 10 to the sixth.

00:57:04.320 --> 00:57:06.360
That's what you would
get from Morse's law.

00:57:06.360 --> 00:57:08.410
40 years is about
when you retire.

00:57:08.410 --> 00:57:10.200
So I mean, I'm
long gone by then,

00:57:10.200 --> 00:57:11.840
but you guys are
going to retire.

00:57:11.840 --> 00:57:14.010
So where will you be?

00:57:14.010 --> 00:57:16.440
Well, let's say we can
do 10 to the 8 atoms.

00:57:16.440 --> 00:57:18.360
So what is that, 100 million?

00:57:18.360 --> 00:57:20.490
The record stands
more at a billion now,

00:57:20.490 --> 00:57:23.792
but nobody kind of performs
at the record all the time.

00:57:23.792 --> 00:57:25.500
You have to essentially
take what you can

00:57:25.500 --> 00:57:27.640
do on an almost daily basis.

00:57:27.640 --> 00:57:29.700
So if you do 100 million
atoms with potentials,

00:57:29.700 --> 00:57:33.510
you'll be able to do
10 to the 14 atoms.

00:57:33.510 --> 00:57:34.560
What does that buy you?

00:57:34.560 --> 00:57:36.668
I'm not totally sure.

00:57:36.668 --> 00:57:39.210
You have to ask yourself, what
can you do with 10 to 14 atoms

00:57:39.210 --> 00:57:41.810
that you can't do
with 10 to the 8?

00:57:41.810 --> 00:57:44.360
Because a lot of things don't
depend on the number of atoms.

00:57:44.360 --> 00:57:46.130
They depend on the length scale.

00:57:46.130 --> 00:57:47.840
And so of course,
the length scale

00:57:47.840 --> 00:57:50.460
is the cube root of
the number of atoms.

00:57:50.460 --> 00:57:52.340
So there, you've
only gained about--

00:57:52.340 --> 00:57:55.530
well, you've gained about a
factor of 100 in length scale.

00:57:55.530 --> 00:57:58.460
But if you go to something
that scales like the cube.

00:57:58.460 --> 00:58:00.950
And I know this is a
little overdoing it--

00:58:00.950 --> 00:58:04.498
LDA scales in large problems is
much more like n squared log n.

00:58:04.498 --> 00:58:06.290
But let's say on smaller
problems it's just

00:58:06.290 --> 00:58:07.730
like the cube of n.

00:58:07.730 --> 00:58:11.330
So if you can do 1,000
atoms now, when you retire,

00:58:11.330 --> 00:58:13.530
you'll be able to
do 100,000 atoms.

00:58:13.530 --> 00:58:17.037
So where is that
going to take us?

00:58:17.037 --> 00:58:19.370
I think it's going to allow
us to do some things that we

00:58:19.370 --> 00:58:20.480
have a hard time with--

00:58:20.480 --> 00:58:25.910
biological species, for example,
where even this is really

00:58:25.910 --> 00:58:27.770
cutting it close.

00:58:27.770 --> 00:58:31.010
You want to do proteins and DNA.

00:58:31.010 --> 00:58:33.840
Yeah, people do dabble in
it now, and you can do it,

00:58:33.840 --> 00:58:37.310
but it's fighting
against the frontier.

00:58:37.310 --> 00:58:39.470
You've got to do solvent,
and so people now

00:58:39.470 --> 00:58:43.040
make more ad hoc models
for including the solvent.

00:58:43.040 --> 00:58:45.890
I think, when you
do 100,000, you

00:58:45.890 --> 00:58:48.170
are going to do
biology much more.

00:58:48.170 --> 00:58:50.930
Are you going to do
mechanical behavior?

00:58:50.930 --> 00:58:51.950
I don't think so.

00:58:51.950 --> 00:58:53.960
Not in the direct
ab initio scale.

00:58:53.960 --> 00:58:57.140
This is probably by no
means enough to sort of span

00:58:57.140 --> 00:59:01.010
the length scale from
atoms to microstructure.

00:59:01.010 --> 00:59:03.570
Of course, if you believe that
we're all going to be doing

00:59:03.570 --> 00:59:06.630
[? LDA ?] [INAUDIBLE],,
now you're up to--

00:59:06.630 --> 00:59:07.880
what is this, a billion atoms?

00:59:07.880 --> 00:59:09.972
So starting to count.

00:59:09.972 --> 00:59:11.680
Of course, when you
have a billion atoms,

00:59:11.680 --> 00:59:13.930
you're going to have to
figure out how to look at them

00:59:13.930 --> 00:59:17.110
and how to extract data from
them, which is non-trivial

00:59:17.110 --> 00:59:19.080
at these large simulations.

00:59:19.080 --> 00:59:21.953
The people who sort of
broke these frontiers--

00:59:21.953 --> 00:59:24.370
there was a group at Louisiana
State that, for the longest

00:59:24.370 --> 00:59:25.472
time, drove this forward.

00:59:25.472 --> 00:59:27.680
And I think they may have
done the first billion atom

00:59:27.680 --> 00:59:29.260
simulation.

00:59:29.260 --> 00:59:34.060
A lot of the research is in
data transfer, data analysis,

00:59:34.060 --> 00:59:36.040
visualization, because
think about it.

00:59:36.040 --> 00:59:38.110
When you have a
billion atoms, how

00:59:38.110 --> 00:59:39.550
do you decide what's going on?

00:59:39.550 --> 00:59:41.910
You just look at it, or like--

00:59:41.910 --> 00:59:45.480
so that's actually a big
chunk of that research.

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:48.060
And then I took one
that's kind of excessive,

00:59:48.060 --> 00:59:51.600
but let's say you do [INAUDIBLE]
configuration interactions,

00:59:51.600 --> 00:59:54.690
which is as close
to-- essentially as

00:59:54.690 --> 00:59:57.000
close to the exact
solution maybe

00:59:57.000 --> 00:59:58.950
that you could get
for quantum mechanics,

00:59:58.950 --> 01:00:00.870
except maybe quantum
Monte Carlo now.

01:00:00.870 --> 01:00:04.740
But that scaling
is depending on who

01:00:04.740 --> 01:00:07.050
you believe is somewhere
from n to the fifth

01:00:07.050 --> 01:00:09.800
to n to the seventh.

01:00:09.800 --> 01:00:11.960
It's such small
numbers that it's not

01:00:11.960 --> 01:00:14.750
even really sure you can
quite calibrate the scaling.

01:00:14.750 --> 01:00:16.880
But so if you can
do 10 atoms now,

01:00:16.880 --> 01:00:20.290
you can only do 100 by
the time you retire.

01:00:20.290 --> 01:00:22.930
So these things are
useful for calibration,

01:00:22.930 --> 01:00:27.490
but they're not going to allow
us to, say, do DNA and do it

01:00:27.490 --> 01:00:28.880
more accurately.

01:00:28.880 --> 01:00:36.470
So the only reason I'm saying
is that you will still not

01:00:36.470 --> 01:00:39.125
be able to rely on Morse's
law for all your problems.

01:00:39.125 --> 01:00:40.500
You still have to
figure out ways

01:00:40.500 --> 01:00:44.360
to, in a sort of smart
way, use computations.

01:00:44.360 --> 01:00:48.540
I always find it funny
the proposals I read of we

01:00:48.540 --> 01:00:51.390
can't quite compute this,
but next year we can.

01:00:51.390 --> 01:00:53.580
Well, most stuff
you can't compute

01:00:53.580 --> 01:00:56.590
today you won't be able to
compute next year either.

01:00:56.590 --> 01:00:59.940
And so you'll still
have to find shortcuts.

01:00:59.940 --> 01:01:03.810
If you count on being able to
sort of put materials in a box,

01:01:03.810 --> 01:01:07.260
and simulate the hell out
of them, and sort of figure

01:01:07.260 --> 01:01:10.050
out what comes up, I
think it's unlikely

01:01:10.050 --> 01:01:13.230
that that will happen
in any reasonable time

01:01:13.230 --> 01:01:14.525
for a lot of properties.

01:01:14.525 --> 01:01:16.150
There are properties
you can do it for.

01:01:16.150 --> 01:01:19.110
But for most things,
I don't think you can.

